THE Competition Commission has referred a collusion case against 17 banks to the Competition Tribunal of SA for prosecution.Three of Mzansi&rsquo;s biggest banks are included among the 17. The commission said it had been investigating a case of price-fixing and market allocation in the trading of foreign currency pairs involving the rand since April 2015.The banks are the Bank of America, Merrill Lynch International Ltd, BNP Paribas, JP Morgan Chase &amp; Co, JP Morgan Chase Bank NA, Investec Ltd, Standard New York Securities Inc, HSBC Bank Plc, Standard Chartered Bank, Credit Suisse Group, Standard Bank of South Africa , Commerzbank AG, Australia &amp; New Zealand Banking Group Ltd, Nomura International, Macquarie Bank, Absa Bank, Barclays Capital Inc and Barclays Bank.The commission is seeking an order from the tribunal declaring that the respondents have contravened the Competitions Act.Further, it is seeking an order declaring that 14 of the banks are liable to pay an administrative penalty equal to 10% of annual turnover. &ndash; Fin24